## Common TDZ Scenarios

### Scenario 1: Callbacks Used in Multiple Effects

```javascript
function MyComponent() {
  const [data, setData] = useState([]);
  
  // ✅ Declare shared callback ONCE at the top
  const processData = useCallback((items) => {
    return items.filter(item => item.active);
  }, []);
  
  // ✅ Use in multiple effects
  useEffect(() => {
    const processed = processData(data);
    console.log(processed);
  }, [data, processData]);
  
  useEffect(() => {
    const processed = processData(initialData);
    setData(processed);
  }, [processData]);
}
```

### Scenario 2: Nested Callbacks

```javascript
function MyComponent() {
  // ✅ Order matters: inner callbacks first
  const innerAction = useCallback(() => {
    // ... implementation
  }, []);
  
  const outerAction = useCallback(() => {
    innerAction(); // ✅ Safe: innerAction declared above
  }, [innerAction]);
  
  useEffect(() => {
    outerAction(); // ✅ Safe: outerAction declared above
  }, [outerAction]);
}
```

---

## Checklist for Avoiding TDZ Errors

- [ ] All `useCallback`/`useMemo` declared before `useEffect` that use them
- [ ] Dependency arrays include all referenced variables
- [ ] No forward references in hook dependencies
- [ ] Callbacks used in multiple effects declared once at component top
- [ ] Test in production build (TDZ may only appear after minification)

---

## ESLint Rule

Enable the React Hooks ESLint plugin:

```json
{
  "extends": ["plugin:react-hooks/recommended"],
  "rules": {
    "react-hooks/exhaustive-deps": "warn"
  }
}
```

This warns about missing dependencies but won't catch TDZ errors. Manual code review is essential.
